Basic hull design 300mm long, prints in three pieces. The pumps are printed assembled and glued together with acetone. Final mounting is up to you but I chose to use a clamp style mount on the end and seal around the intake and output with hot glue. The boat can also be used with any type of RC boat propulsion on the market of the appropriate size.  
Boat hull bottom will be coated in marine epoxy, primer, paint, and clear coat to make it stronger.   
Impellers are designed to be press fit and glued to a 3mm axle with 3mmID 6mm OD bearings and a 3mm ID 6mmOD rubber groment to keep water out. Then with a 30mm pulley at a right angle to a 10mm  pulley on the drive motor which will drive both pumps.   
The Pilot hole on top of each pump is for a water nipple to be added at a later date for water cooling to the motor, esc, and battery.  
Update 4/21/14: I apologize to everyone who has been making this that the top files were incomplete. I have added the last file (Top2.stl) and will be posting pictures of my build soon. Weather is starting to get nicer here so might be able to even get some action vid as soon as I can get to the lake.   
Update 11/6/13: I ditched the belt drive pumps because there was to much draw on one motor and the belts were hard to keep on the pulleys at high speeds. I designed a direct drive version which uses a 34mm bolt pattern standard with most 28mm brushless outrunner mounting plates. The shaft of the outrunners was removed and a brass one inserted to help with cooling and provide a longer shaft to reach the impellers. Also added a 3 piece top design to the boat which was glued on and a cover will be made at a later date.

10/25/11 revised my pump design to use a 3mm shaft with a 'D' milled in each end for the pulley and impeller to grab into. At full throttle the belts fell off the pulleys and after adding an idler point and making the main 30mm pulley bigger the problem was solved. Updated Revised pump.zip with up to date pump design.

description.text:
This is a PCB clamp / vice / helping hand that's quite easy to print with no supports. Just be sure to use at least 4 shells and then you can do 10% infill with no problems.

There's a ball joint on the cleat so you can loosen and tighten while keeping the slots on each end of the clamp aligned

It's designed for a 1/4-20 threaded rod and requires tapping a few holes post-printing. I printed it in PLA and it worked fine. Just tap slowly and be sure your chips are being cleared.

This was a quick design and experiment and my first upload. I wanted to play with ball joint design/printing and tolerancing for tapping. It worked out quite well. Feel free to remix. Enjoy!

description.text:
This is a fan mount that I designed in Tinkercad for my RP9 v2 printer from http://www.bobscnc.com. The clip fits snugly in the space between zip ties holding the Y linear bearings on either side of the hot end assembly. Print one for each side to ensure even cooling.

The mount fits a 40 mm fan and is a tight fit in the printer. The fan should be mounted on the underside of the clip using M3 screws - guessing 30-35 mm long. The 30 degree tilt was picked to fit some air ducts of similar angle. However, due to mounting constraints none of the designs I've found are short enough to fit. Please be aware that the dimensions of the RP9 and 40 mm fans make for a tight fit. Depending on where you have zip ties, you may find yourself bumping into them when the hot end is going home.

When running, the two fans will cool the hot end a bit and will require the heating block to work a bit harder to maintain temperature. I have had no issues with maintaining 190-210 degrees C for PLA, but I've not tried higher temperatures. Your mileage may vary.

This design is the sixth iteration and I will not likely make any additional changes.

description.text:
As you can tell, I like to accessorize my vehicles, this is a great mount for holding your iPhone 6s Plus, or iPhone 6 Plus. It mounts your + out of the way, easily visible, and high enough to clear even the bulky factory key as you can see in one of the pictures.

The original design was a much thicker base that had a recessed stem mount, but I realized after building it that the thick base wasn't needed, and was just a waste of build material.

For fitment, slide the bolt through the top of the unit (the head will recess to protect your phone), then slide the stem beneath, then use a small piece of rubber hose and a nut. As you tighten the screw, the nut will grab the rubber hose and start to compress it the rubber hose and squeeze the sides of the motorcycle stem mount making it secure.

Additional Materials:
• Rubber Hose - roughly 12 mm diameter and only about 12 mm long. I found mine randomly in a drawer so....FREE! :)
• Bolt and nut - I can't give a length since I don't know what size hose you're going to use. Take the mount and rubber hose to a hardware store and try some on. DO NOT GET A THREAD LOCK NUT! This design only works if the nut can freely move about without a wrench. And don't worry, once you tighten it all down on your bike, that nut isn't going anywhere. As you can see from the pictures, my Hayabusa is lowered, and has thin tires because of the custom wheels, mine hasn't vibrated loose, and neither will yours.

Since most Suzuki have the same neck setup, it SHOULD fit a lot of different bikes. I highly recommend you print just the iPhone stem first, slide it in and measure before printing the entire thing only to find out that it's too low, or the mount extends too far and hits the tank.
Tested on:
2007 Suzuki Hayabusa
2010 Suzuki Hayabusa
2005 Suzuki GSXR 600

Wall hook

This is a hook to support a Cold-RolLED Weldable Steel Metal Round (a solid pipe). This pipe will sustain 6 wire spool. The system involves 2 of these hooks, the pipe and two screws (6- 1 1/2) to attach the hooks to a shelf.

Design process

I decided to make my own holder for a set of wire spool for the soldering area in my lab.

I took the measures from the wire spool.
I found a piece of Cold-RolLED Weldable Steel Metal Round (a solid pipe) that fitted to the measures (diameter) to the wire spool hole and long enough to sustain 6 wire spool.
I calculate the screw size according to the expected weight.
I measured the distance between the base (attached part to the surface to sustain the system in this case a shelf) and the pipe that will sustain the wire spools (that distance has to clear the size of the half of the wire spool diameter).
Using the measures for the base and the distance from base to pipe I created the base and the hook as separately pieces in Thinkercad and then I attached them to create only one object. making a hole with the diameter of the cylindrical metal part in the hook.
I create the holes for a pan wood screw with freason drive (6-1 1/2) on the base (2 holes)

title: RigidBot Original LCD Buttons
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Replacement buttons for the original RigidBot LCD display supplied with soft rubber keys.

I could no longer put up with the soft, constantly sticking LCD panel keys on our original RigidBot. If you have the same problem, here are some replacement keys I designed. Replacing the keys requires removing the LCD panel and then removing the four screws that hold the LCD electronics into the cover. Lift out the LCD circuit board and exchange the keys. (You need one BigBut and four LitBut keys.)

The RigidBot must be off, and unplugged from the AC line. Use ESD precautions when handling the electronics (just google "simple ESD precautions" if you don't know what ESD is) and be careful to plug the LCD back in correctly before applying power.

Not responsible for any damage or injuries that may occur from someone downloading, attempting to print and install the button keys.

Why no R on the center round key like the original? No way to hold the center key in position so the R would be constantly "rolling" out of position. If you really want an R - it is only a remix away, but don't blame me if you develop an overwhelming need to constantly straighten that R up.

title: Versacopter GoPro Session and Boardcam mount

description.text:
This mount allows a GoPro Session and a 32mm board camera to be mounted side by side on the front of a Flite Test Versacopter V2 (never test fit on a V1).

To secure the mount to the top plate, four M3x8 or M3x10 screws and nuts are required. A narrow velcro strap is required to restrain the GoPro from above and a small layer of foam between the camera and mount to tension the camera against the velcro is also required. To mount the board cam (28mm mounting hole spacing for a 32mm cam), you will need four M2x6 screws if threading into the mount or longer screws if using nuts. I have printed and flown this mount without issue. Using 6-inch props, a small amount of prop is visible in frame in each cam as a result of the cams being located so close to the edges of the top plate. I have not crash tested it but have no reservations about it's strength.

Pics are missing my VTX and antenna, as I am reworking the VTX mount.

Hi!

This is my printable version of the classic etch-a-sketch / telesketch. A kind of plotter-toy.

You can draw what you imagine rotating the X-Y knobs.

It works great with a marker or a pen.
The drawing area it's 15x10cms aprox.
The X-axis acts moving the complete paper, inspired in the Prusa Y-axis (moving all bed)

It has many parts and can print mostly without supports (i hate supports)

I've arrange the parts in 6 files according to impression parameters and print order.

Included a PDF with assemblig instructions and some tips.
Included a ZIP file with al the STL files for each part.
Also included the 123D Design files.

See the Print Settings.

And last: Sorry if my english it's not good, i'm from spain and have a bad grammar writting in english.

UPDATE!! The ZIP file 'all_parts_separated_update.zip now contains the STL's with all the pieces 'merged' (old files may cause problems with some slicing software').
Redownload if you have problems with separated parts in the STL's

Custom Nikon Flash grid.
Adding a grid to your flash helps to control where the light spread goes in your scene. It allows you light up specific things like hair or eyes, without adding light everywhere. Different girds can give you different effects so I thought it be cool to make some custom grids and experiment.
These grids are for a Nikon Speedlight SB-600, but it would be really easy to customize them for any flash.

Step 1: Measure front element of the flash with calipers and draw outline in Adobe Illustrator.  
Step 2: Imported the SVG into Tinkercad.  
Step 3: Make a body for the grid that is larger then the flash outline. Set the flash outline to "Hole" and flip everything upside down.  
Step 4: Create a grid to focus the light. In my first print I used the Voronoi Shape Script.

title: Current Meter for DC C02 LASER Tube

description.text: My RECI-brand C02 LASER tube is designed to run at 28 mA. The manufacturer says to keep it at 26 mA if you would like the 10,000 hour life. With my cutter, I could not use 100% power and stay within these limits. In fact, my power has to be set to 77% to be at 26 mA. Make the enclosure from glued 5mm wood or Acrylic, and install a 30mA meter meter in it. I used this one: http://www.ebay.com/itm/Plastic-Class-2-5-Accuracy-DC-0-30MA-Milliamp-Ammeter-Meter-Panel-/321062760680?ssPageName=ADME:L:OC:US:3160 Wire the meter in series with the wire that connects to the LASER tube near the emitter. If the needle moves to the left, then reverse the polarity. You can then adjust your power supply to put out the recommended max current when your software is asking for 100%. For my Z4 tube, that is 28 mA.

description.text:
please note that this is intended at being a display piece not a working part though it could be adapted for that.

The story of how this came to be is kind of an interesting one. The Youtuber Maker's Muse kept mentioning that if he were to design a 3d printer that he would use ball screws instead of lead screws. That got me quite curious as to what in the world he was talking about as I am currently a engineering student in college. Upon researching what a ball screw was I found there to be a lack of quality 3d animations for ball screws. I'm always up for a good 3d design challenge and I figured what the heck I'll give it a shot. This is what I ended up with. I was only able to get 7 out of 59 bearing balls animated due to PC performance limitations with SolidWorks. Once I had the animation done I figured why not go a step further and make it a desktop model. I "cut" the side of the return tube so you could see the bearing balls moving.

Finished product

If for some unknown reason you decide to print this then you will need the follows
PRINT
1 Threaded Rod End
atleast 2 threaded rod middles
2 Threaded Rod Supports
1 Handle
1 Ball screw

BUY
a section of 10mm rod
59 1/4in bearing balls

I assembled it using some 5 min epoxy and some assorted screws I found lying around the house.

title: my new ultralight micro FPV quad frame for micro scisky, 7x20mm motors and 600TVL+TX5823

description.text:
My new design using my own 3D printer! The goal was to make a very light frame so i can carry as heavy a battery as possible. The arms are designed to minimise blocking the airflow from the props, and the motors easily snap into the holders (push up from below and tilt the top inbetween the top clips).
It has an optional "hard top" that neatly snaps into the slots on each side to protect the contents and add some extra rigidity with minimal weight. Also added vertical spikes to easily rubberband the battery to the belly (see photos).

I prefer to keep my drones modular so the camera+TX form a neat FPV backpack, sitting in the front. Use a few drops of hot glue to hold the FCB and the FPV backpack in place.

Flies very well, didn't crash yet so don't know how much it can survive :)

Since i'm printing on super-sticky BuildTak, lifted the flat base so it can be removed from the bed :) So a printer with decent bridging capabilities is a must (i use an active cooling fan).

Enjoy!

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/iJsiKdZOv4X
